comment: Loved the message of aligning with what matters most :) Also, I surprised myself by straightening my leg on the right side! The left side was more challenging, so I just moved my leg in and out a few times before settling in a position with my knee bent & holding my ankle :) Compared to the Move series we are moving much slower... Sometimes it feels very slow, but this way we also have the time to really get into the movements :)

Why *did* I start this practice... what a great question I haven‚Äôt asked myself.  As with everything, the answer is ‚Äúcomplicated‚Äù... a dance major was required to take the ‚Äòbody modalities‚Äô course, taught by Allison Green‚Äîa highly trained dancer and yogi‚Äî in which we covered so many techniques to addressing the body. Feldenkrais, Alexander, gyotechnics, Rolfing, Pilates, and a slew of other techniques were covered. But daily, we practiced yoga. We worked up to holding poses for two full minutes‚Äîour bodies screaming for release as she walked around to analyze our form as suggest corrections (my right knee was my key problem area and I remember her sweet whisper near my ear, ‚Äúrotate from the hip, externally, drawing the knee open and over the pinky toe.‚Äù
I signed up for the class because it was required for my major. By the end of the semester, I had grown by 3/4 of an inch and my knee pain had changed. I continued practicing because it brought me peace and centering through my undergrad. Now I continue daily because studies show that stretching daily helps to prevent the formation of cancer.

Ofc, I've got a long way to go, but I'm so glad to have stuck to the programme so far! Also, Adrienne is such a supportive teacher, even if she can't see me or anything, her small comments like "we'll catch you if you fall" are exactly what I need to keep on going, to get through and keep on trying for the pose even if it feels impossible to me. Also, the comments are always so positive and nice, everyone is trying their best and supporting each other. Thank you, Adrienne, for such a wonderful series of videos, and wonderful channel that fosters such community full of love and support. üíñ

Adriene, I have so much to say to you and have no idea where else I can say it than here... so I really hope you see this. I've been attempting your Yoga Revolution series since the beginning of the year, but have always fallen off the wagon. The first time it was around day 15, the 2nd time it was day 21, the 3rd time I barely got far at all... and now 11 days into the 4th attempt, things are starting to click and I'm wondering if what I'm feeling now is exactly what you intended with this series all along. 

Last night doing your Thoughtfulness practice, I kept my eyes closed the entire time and really took it to heart. I felt a sensation that I've never felt during yoga...I suppose it's what it means to "feel" mindfulness? With my eyes closed, it's as though I could feel how every movement being done was affecting the muscles of my body, and it made me sort of tingly and lightheaded. I couldn't even really open my eyes because I was feeling everything all at once so intensely. It was so odd but also something special, so I started doing research on kundalini awakenings. There have been so many crazy things going on in my life since the end of 2015 when my father passed away, and I've had a couple magical "spiritual awakening" journeys where I've felt like I'm getting somewhere, but I didn't realize that doing yoga could activate similar feelings. Then in doing today's practice I could really see how you plan all of these to fit together like a puzzle. Yesterday it was about thoughtfulness...paying attention to what was going on in the body, and today it was taking those ideas and focusing on making it all work together to serve your body as a whole. It's like learning vs applying what you learned. You give rest and work where you see fit, which is why this series works so well!   

I was drawn to your videos years ago, but wasn't ready to fully commit until this year, but even then... stuff has been really rough and I feel like until last night I didn't truly GET it. Even now I feel like it's just the beginning, but it's SO EXCITING I had to say something! Your authenticity and positivity is so refreshing. Your words move me every day, and get me through the hardest times where I feel like I can't even get out of bed and function at all. I love how you stress finding your own way, accepting and honoring where you're at today. If I miss a day, it affects my whole being...even my fiance notices! Girl, this is powerful stuff!

In past attempts I've gotten choked up and shed a few tears during certain practices, but today during the balancing segment where you said "way to be human," tears just started flowing down my cheeks because I feel like I FINALLY understand. Or at least I'm starting to. I never realized that this would lead to something so valuable and precious... activating this hidden potential within. And it makes sense... this is what you've been trying to do all along, haven't you? I really hope that others watching your videos have felt something similar, because I really do feel like you have embraced what it truly means to be human, and you're doing such good work in attempting to spread that magic to the world. 

Even though this is through the internet, I consider you my guru, and this channel my shaktipat on the journey to fully awaken that hidden potential. I am so, so grateful that you exist and that I somehow have kept finding my way back to you. Everything is aligning!!! Thank you SO so much for continuing to create these videos and being so honest. You have changed my life, and clearly thousands of others. This truly is a revolution :) Namaste <3

Only eleven days of practicing and I feel different. Small, subtle, mostly undetectable by anyone other than I. But the difference is very much present. As am I, it's not frequent. It's not constant. Sometimes my observer is thrown into the tornado of my life situations. It goes missing for moments, but my observer always finds a way back. And I am endlessly thankful because deciding to show up here has made the moments of my observer longer and deeper. More intense. My mom has terrible lower back problems, and I have inherited them but there is still hope to guide them into a less painful future as I'm still young. I work as a barista so I'm on my feet a lot! I think I've gotten sciatica in my right leg. It flairs up sometimes, but the way I stand throughout my day and the thoughtfulness I put into it-directly affects it. I have less pain because of my practice. I have less pain because everyday for longer periods I am aware of me equally distributing my weight on either feet. I am aware of my balance and posture more and more every second. The practice on the mat DOES effect my every day practice off the mat and I am forever grateful to myself for showing up. Like another yogi friend said, it is no longer a chore. It feels damn good to show up and be here with you Adriene and everyone else! I am so thankful for you. As I grew up and became more spiritual and more conscious and aware of myself, I found yoga but felt it was a lost cause in the western world because of the financial weight of it. I thought, "what if yoga is the tool to save someone, but they cannot afford it?" (Expensive classes, retreats, etc) Fortunately, there are people like you that do offer those things but ALSO offer an array of videos free. And I know that's not always easy to offer free services for people. So I get it. But I am forever thankful that a cosmic dust created you and you are here, to create a healing practice with and for us. You are so appreciated!! Thanks for helping me find what feels good!!
